ChatGPT said:

To implement the dropdown functionality for the "About" menu item in your NavBar.tsx, we can modify the NavBar component to display a dropdown with "Our Mission," "Our Vision," and "Our Values" when the user hovers over the "About" link. Here's how you can achieve that:

Updated NavBar.tsx with Dropdown Functionality

tsx
"use client";

import { useState } from 'react';
import Link from 'next/link';
import styles from '../styless/Navbar.module.css';

const NavBar = () => {
  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);
  const [isDropdownOpen, setIsDropdownOpen] = useState(false);

  const toggleMenu = () => {
    setIsOpen(!isOpen);
  };

  const closeMenu = () => {
    setIsOpen(false);
  };

  const toggleDropdown = () => {
    setIsDropdownOpen(!isDropdownOpen);
  };

  return (
    <nav className={styles.nav}>
      <div className={styles.logo}>
        <Link href="/">MEL Laundry</Link>
      </div>
      <button className={styles.toggleButton} onClick={toggleMenu}>
        {isOpen ? '✕' : '☰'}
      </button>
      <ul className={`${styles.navList} ${isOpen ? styles.show : ''}`}>
        <li key="/" onClick={closeMenu}>
          <Link href="/">Home</Link>
        </li>

        {/* Dropdown for About */}
        <li
          className={styles.dropdown}
          onMouseEnter={toggleDropdown}
          onMouseLeave={toggleDropdown}
        >
          <span className={styles.navLink}>About</span>
          <ul className={`${styles.dropdownMenu} ${isDropdownOpen ? styles.showDropdown : ''}`}>
            <li key="/about/mission">
              <Link href="/about/mission" onClick={closeMenu}>Our Mission</Link>
            </li>
            <li key="/about/vision">
              <Link href="/about/vision" onClick={closeMenu}>Our Vision</Link>
            </li>
            <li key="/about/values">
              <Link href="/about/values" onClick={closeMenu}>Our Values</Link>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li key="/service">
          <Link href="/service" onClick={closeMenu}>Services</Link>
        </li>
        <li key="/blog">
          <Link href="/blog" onClick={closeMenu}>Blog</Link>
        </li>
        <li key="/contact">
          <Link href="/contact" onClick={closeMenu}>Contact</Link>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </nav>
  );
};

export default NavBar;

ChatGPT said:

The issue here is related to how CSS Modules handle global selectors like :root. CSS Modules are designed to scope CSS to the component level to avoid global styles affecting other parts of your application. To solve this issue, you have a couple of options:

Option 1: Use Global Styles

If you want to keep the :root selector, you should place it in a global CSS file instead of a CSS Module. In Next.js, you can include global CSS files in your _app.js or _app.tsx.

  1. Create a Global CSS File:

    • Move the :root selector and other global styles into a file named globals.css (or similar).
    • For example:
    css
    /* styles/globals.css */

:root {
  --primary-green: #2ecc71;
  --dark-green: #27ae60;
  --light-green: #eafaf1;
  --white: #ffffff;
  --black: #333333;
  --dropdown-bg: #ffffff;
  --dropdown-border: #27ae60;
}

/* Other global styles */

  2. Import Global CSS in _app.js:

    js
    // pages/_app.js

import '../styles/globals.css';
import '../styles/Navbar.module.css'; // Import CSS Module here if needed

function MyApp({ Component, pageProps }) {
  return <Component {...pageProps} />;
}

export default MyApp;

Option 2: Use CSS Variables Directly in Components

If you want to use CSS Modules for everything, you can define your CSS variables directly within components where they're needed.

  1. Define Variables in Component Styles:

    • Move the :root variables to the component-specific CSS Modules.
    css
    /* styles/Navbar.module.css */

.container {
  --primary-green: #2ecc71;
  --dark-green: #27ae60;
  --light-green: #eafaf1;
  --white: #ffffff;
  --black: #333333;
  --dropdown-bg: #ffffff;
  --dropdown-border: #27ae60;

  background-color: var(--primary-green);
  /* Rest of your styles */
}

  2. Apply Styles in the Component:

    jsx
    // components/Navbar.jsx

import styles from '../styles/Navbar.module.css';

const Navbar = () => {
  return (
    <nav className={styles.container}>
      {/* Navbar content */}
    </nav>
  );
};

export default Navbar;

Summary

For global variables like :root, the preferred approach is to use a global CSS file. This way, your global styles are properly scoped and do not interfere with the CSS Modules' scoping mechanism. After making these changes, restart your Next.js server to apply the updates.

ChatGPT said:

It looks like you're encountering an issue with using the :root selector in CSS modules. By default, CSS modules are designed to scope styles locally to components, and the :root selector, which is a global selector, conflicts with this design.

Here are a few ways to address this issue:

1. Use Global CSS

Instead of putting your global variables in a CSS module, you can create a global CSS file. Next.js supports global CSS files and you can use them to define global styles and variables.

  • Create a file named globals.css in your styles directory (e.g., app/styles/globals.css).
css
/* globals.css */
:root {
  --primary-green: #2ecc71;
  --dark-green: #27ae60;
  --light-green: #eafaf1;
  --white: #ffffff;
  --black: #333333;
  --dropdown-bg: #ffffff;
  --dropdown-border: #27ae60;
}

/* Other global styles */
  • Import this global CSS file in your _app.tsx (or _app.js if using JavaScript):
tsx
// _app.tsx
import '../styles/globals.css'; // Adjust the path as needed

function MyApp({ Component, pageProps }) {
  return <Component {...pageProps} />;
}

export default MyApp;

2. Inline Styles

If the styles are not too complex and you prefer not to use a global stylesheet, you can use inline styles or CSS-in-JS libraries to define these variables.

For example, using inline styles with React:

jsx
const rootStyles = {
  '--primary-green': '#2ecc71',
  '--dark-green': '#27ae60',
  '--light-green': '#eafaf1',
  '--white': '#ffffff',
  '--black': '#333333',
  '--dropdown-bg': '#ffffff',
  '--dropdown-border': '#27ae60'
};

const MyComponent = () => (
  <div style={rootStyles}>
    {/* Your component JSX */}
  </div>
);

3. CSS-in-JS Libraries

Alternatively, you can use a CSS-in-JS library like styled-components or emotion which allow for defining global styles:

  • Using styled-components:

    bash
    npm install styled-components

    jsx
    // styles.js
import { createGlobalStyle } from 'styled-components';

const GlobalStyle = createGlobalStyle`
  :root {
    --primary-green: #2ecc71;
    --dark-green: #27ae60;
    --light-green: #eafaf1;
    --white: #ffffff;
    --black: #333333;
    --dropdown-bg: #ffffff;
    --dropdown-border: #27ae60;
  }
`;

export default GlobalStyle;

    jsx
    // _app.tsx
import GlobalStyle from '../styles/styles'; // Adjust the path as needed

function MyApp({ Component, pageProps }) {
  return (
    <>
      <GlobalStyle />
      <Component {...pageProps} />
    </>
  );
}

export default MyApp;

Summary

To fix the error, you should move the :root selector and other global styles into a global CSS file or use a CSS-in-JS approach to define your global variables. This way, you'll avoid conflicts with CSS modules and keep your styles organized.
